  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-953">
    <command xml:space="preserve">close purple</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You close the purple capsa of opening.&#x000A;&#x000A;From everywhere in the Aerie, you hear the woodpeckers drumming in the Pounding dialect: "Reset Locks!  Repeat!  Reset Locks!&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 2.&#x000A;A squad of Raven Guards appears, and their war cries exalt as they spot you.  You weave through the air, tumbling and twisting as you try to avoid them.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-954"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-954">
    <command xml:space="preserve">z</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Time passes.&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 3.&#x000A;The guards charge, but you manage to evade their uncoordinated attack.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-955"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-955">
    <command xml:space="preserve">scenes</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Scene 'Entire Game' playing (for 6 mins now)&#x000A;Scene 'Starting Off' playing (for 6 mins now)&#x000A;Scene 'Everything Is Open' ended&#x000A;Scene 'Reset Sensors' playing (for 2 mins now)&#x000A;Scene 'Doors Re-close' playing (for 2 mins now)&#x000A;Scene 'Being Chased' playing (for 3 mins now)&#x000A;(Scene monitoring now switched on. Type "scenes off" to switch it off again.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1146">
    <command xml:space="preserve">take off rucksack</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You take off the leather rucksack.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-1147"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1147">
    <command xml:space="preserve">summon mist</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-1148"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1148">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open purple</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You open the purple capsa of opening, revealing a scroll of rezrov.&#x000A;&#x000A;As you open the purple capsa, an almost-palpable wave of force emanates from it, as the power of the revealed scroll of rezrov is released.&#x000A;&#x000A;The magic of the gold capsa of down prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;The magic of the red capsa of hasten prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;&#x000A;From... well, from everywhere in the Aerie, it seems, Woodpeckers start drumming out messages in their Pounding dialect:  "Intruder! Estimated direction is..." and then each one individually seems to be telegraphing the direction from them to you.  You can't discern any one drummer from any other drummer, but you can at least tell that each seems to be drumming on sheets of metal that differ from each other, as the frequencies are all different from each other.  That makes the information somewhat useless to you, because you've not been trained to distinguish Pounding at different frequencies.  And because you already know where you are.  Sadly, the Raven Guards are indeed trained to distinguish Pounding frequencies.&#x000A;&#x000A;And if they didn't know where you were, they do now.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-1149"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1149">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors of the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You've dived straight into a squad of Raven Guards, on their way up to accost you.  Fortunately, your speed helped you avoid most of them, but one guard's talon catches you on your side as you twist by them.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-1150"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1150">
    <command xml:space="preserve">u</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal Quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;The Raven Guard pursues you determinedly through the thin mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-1151"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1151">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You tuck in your wings and dive down  towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors of the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;Your speed puts more distance between you and your pursuers, but it's not quite fast enough, or the mist isn't thick enough, or both, and your pursuers manage to keep you in sight.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-1152"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-1152">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;You expertly twist at breakneck speeds, weaving through three Ash trunks, over a branch, and around and behind a Redwood, where you halt, twist, and dive straight down the trunk, out of view of any stray Raven.&#x000A;&#x000A;The Raven's frustrated caws echo in the mist.  In time, the woodpeckers cease their drumming, and the cawing fades as well.  Protocol would dictate that they return to guarding priority items.  If there were any reserves left, they would be called up, but the Red Plague has affected the Raven Guard as sorely as your own community.&#x000A;&#x000A;You &#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;                                                             *    *    *</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-562">
    <command xml:space="preserve">test horatio_speedrun</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] summon mist&#x000A;Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] d&#x000A;You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors of the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal Quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] open purple&#x000A;You open the purple capsa of opening, revealing a scroll of rezrov.&#x000A;&#x000A;As you open the purple capsa, an almost-palpable wave of force emanates from it, as the power of the revealed scroll of rezrov is released.&#x000A;&#x000A;The magic of the gold capsa of down prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;The magic of the red capsa of hasten prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;The straps and buckles on your rucksack fly open and it falls!&#x000A;&#x000A;The leather rucksack twists away as it falls below you, towards the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;From... well, from everywhere in the Aerie, it seems, Woodpeckers start drumming out messages in their Pounding dialect:  "Intruder! Estimated direction is..." and then each one individually seems to be telegraphing the direction from them to you.  You can't discern any one drummer from any other drummer, but you can at least tell that each seems to be drumming on sheets of metal that differ from each other, as the frequencies are all different from each other.  That makes the information somewhat useless to you, because you've not been trained to distinguish Pounding at different frequencies.  And because you already know where you are.  Sadly, the Raven Guards are indeed trained to distinguish Pounding frequencies.&#x000A;&#x000A;And if they didn't know where you were, they do now.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[5] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down  towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors of the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see a leather rucksack (in which are a purple capsa of opening (in which is a scroll of rezrov), a gold capsa of down (closed), and a red capsa of hasten (closed)) here.&#x000A;&#x000A;You've dived straight into a squad of Raven Guards, on their way up to accost you.  Fortunately, your speed helped you avoid most of them, but one guard's talon catches you on your side as you twist by them.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[6] d&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;You expertly twist at breakneck speeds, weaving through three Ash trunks, over a branch, and around and behind a Redwood, where you halt, twist, and dive straight down the trunk, out of view of any stray Raven.&#x000A;&#x000A;The Raven's frustrated caws echo in the mist.  In time, the woodpeckers cease their drumming, and the cawing fades as well.  Protocol would dictate that they return to guarding priority items.  If there were any reserves left, they would be called up, but the Red Plague has affected the Raven Guard as sorely as your own community.&#x000A;&#x000A;You retrieve your rucksack and any fallen capsae, and plot a now-unseen course back to the familiar currents above the Aerie to ponder your next move.&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;                                                             *    *    *</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] summon mist&#x000A;Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] d&#x000A;You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors of the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal Quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] open purple&#x000A;You open the purple capsa of opening, revealing a scroll of rezrov.&#x000A;&#x000A;As you open the purple capsa, an almost-palpable wave of force emanates from it, as the power of the revealed scroll of rezrov is released.&#x000A;&#x000A;The magic of the gold capsa of down prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;The magic of the red capsa of hasten prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;The straps and buckles on your rucksack fly open and it falls!&#x000A;&#x000A;The leather rucksack twists away as it falls below you, towards the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;From... well, from everywhere in the Aerie, it seems, Woodpeckers start drumming out messages in their Pounding dialect:  "Intruder! Estimated direction is..." and then each one individually seems to be telegraphing the direction from them to you.  You can't discern any one drummer from any other drummer, but you can at least tell that each seems to be drumming on sheets of metal that differ from each other, as the frequencies are all different from each other.  That makes the information somewhat useless to you, because you've not been trained to distinguish Pounding at different frequencies.  And because you already know where you are.  Sadly, the Raven Guards are indeed trained to distinguish Pounding frequencies.&#x000A;&#x000A;And if they didn't know where you were, they do now.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[5] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors of the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see a leather rucksack (in which are a purple capsa of opening (in which is a scroll of rezrov), a gold capsa of down (closed), and a red capsa of hasten (closed)) here.&#x000A;&#x000A;You've dived straight into a squad of Raven Guards, on their way up to accost you.  Fortunately, your speed helped you avoid most of them, but one guard's talon catches you on your side as you twist by them.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[6] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down into the forest below the Aerie, dodging tightly-spaced trees with acrobatic precision.&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;You expertly twist at breakneck speeds, weaving through three Ash trunks, over a branch, and around and behind a Redwood, where you halt, twist, and dive straight down the trunk, out of view of any stray Raven.&#x000A;&#x000A;The Raven's frustrated caws echo in the mist.  In time, the woodpeckers cease their drumming, and the cawing fades as well.  Protocol would dictate that they return to guarding priority items.  If there were any reserves left, they would be called up, but the {LS DEBUG: DISEASE} has affected the Raven Squad as sorely as your own community.&#x000A;&#x000A;You retrieve your rucksack plot a now-unseen course back to the familiar currents above the Aerie to ponder your next move.&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;                                                             *    *    *</commentary>
